│                                                                                            │
│ The problem is that the order of scalars in this `SplitVectorize` node is incorrect. The   │
│ `extractelement` instructions are not grouped together at the beginning, which violates    │
│ the assumption made later during the `vectorizeTree` process.                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ The root cause lies in the `BoUpSLP::buildTree` function, specifically in how it handles   │
│ reused scalars when creating a `SplitVectorize` node.                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ When the vectorizer decides to split a `TreeEntry` because its operands come from          │
│ different sources, it creates a new `SplitVectorize` entry. The scalars for this new entry │
│ are a concatenation of the scalars from the two source entries.                            │
│                                                                                            │
│ The code in `buildTree` that performs this concatenation is:                               │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                         │
│ // In BoUpSLP::buildTree                                                                   │
│ ...                                                                                        │
│ if (isa<ExtractElementInst>(Scalar1) && isa<ExtractElementInst>(Scalar2)) {                │
│ ...                                                                                        │
│ } else if (isa<ExtractElementInst>(Scalar1) && !isa<ExtractElementInst>(Scalar2)) {        │
│   // Create a new Entry for the list of scalars.                                           │
│   // The new entry is a split-vectorization entry.                                         │
│   TreeEntry *TE = new TreeEntry(E->getOpcode());                                           │
│   TE->State = TreeEntry::SplitVectorize;                                                   │
│   TE->setOperands(OpTE1, OpTE2);                                                           │
│   TE->Scalars.append(OpTE1->Scalars.begin(), OpTE1->Scalars.end());                        │
│   TE->Scalars.append(OpTE2->Scalars.begin(), OpTE2->Scalars.end());                        │
│   // ...                                                                                   │
│ }                                                                                          │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│ The issue is that `OpTE1` and `OpTE2` might not correspond to the `MainOp` and `AltOp` of  │
│ the original entry `E`. The code incorrectly assumes a specific ordering of operands which │
│ is not guaranteed. In this case, `OpTE1` contains the `load` instructions, while `OpTE2`   │
│ contains the `extractelement` instructions. However, the `MainOp` of `E` is an             │
│ `extractelement`.                                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The `vectorizeTree` function later retrieves the operand entries based on `E->MainOp` and  │
│ `E->AltOp`. It expects the scalars of `E` to be ordered according to the operands of       │
│ `E->MainOp` followed by `E->AltOp`. But `buildTree` ordered them as `OpTE1` then `OpTE2`.  │
│ This mismatch leads to the assertion failure.                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to ensure that when creating the `SplitVectorize` entry, the scalars are        │
│ appended in the correct order, matching the `MainOp` and `AltOp` of the original entry     │
│ `E`.                                                                                       │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to reorder the `OpTE1` and `OpTE2` operands in `buildTree` to match the         │
│ structure of the original `TreeEntry` `E`.                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```patch                                                                                   │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                      │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                      │
│ @@ -15888,6 +15888,11 @@                                                                   │
│        // The new entry is a split-vectorization entry.                                    │
│        TreeEntry *TE = new TreeEntry(E->getOpcode());                                      │
│        TE->State = TreeEntry::SplitVectorize;                                              │
│ +      // Make sure that we order the operands so that the first operand of the            │
│ +      // new entry is the same as the first operand of the original entry.                │
│ +      if (OpTE1->Scalars[0] != E->getOperand(0)->getOperand(0))                           │
│ +        std::swap(OpTE1, OpTE2);                                                          │
│ +                                                                                          │
│        TE->setOperands(OpTE1, OpTE2);                                                      │
│        TE->Scalars.append(OpTE1->Scalars.begin(), OpTE1->Scalars.end());                   │
│        TE->Scalars.append(OpTE2->Scalars.begin(), OpTE2->Scalars.end());                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ This change ensures that `OpTE1` always corresponds to the `MainOp`'s operand chain, and   │
│ `OpTE2` to the `AltOp`'s. This restores the invariant that `vectorizeTree` relies on.      │
│                                                                                            │
